gitlab2prov2d6aff22-aeaa-59a7-8fab-25474.gitlab2provevent_content:
> I used to explicitly specify to fetch English-language results, whereas the SPARQL query doesn't show anything like that. It doesn't appear to affect the results yet, I hope it won't do so in the future either.

Humm, I'm not sure this is a problem. These URLs are all redirects/aliases to the same website, right? Or are there language-specific versions of Sci-Hub that some of these URLs point to?

> You select all URLs with a `NormalRank`, whereas I previously showed everything without a deprecated rank. I'm assuming that `?mainUrl` achieves the same? It's not clear to me where `?mainUrl` and `?otherUrls` come from - is that defined in the "official website" property?

[There are three possible ranks](https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Help:Ranking#Usage) for statements: preferred, normal and deprecated. Technically, the deprecated rank should not be used for correct historical data (data that used to be correct but is not anymore); that should be modeled by start date/end date qualifiers instead. But since in practice that is how the discontinued URLs for Sci-Hub are annotated, it suffices to use that for the time being.

The `wdt:` (which is a built-in alias for the `http://www.wikidata.org/prop/direct/` SPARQL prefix) picks up only the statements marked as preferred. I'm not yet sure how it handles the cases of zero or multiple statements marked as preferred, but again, for practical purposes, we can use it for Sci-Hub since it seems to typically retain a single preferred official website.

The query above is actually two queries, merged via an `UNION` operation. The `?mainUrl` part returns the official website statement marked with the preferred rank, and the `?otherUrls` part returns the official website statements marked as normal rank (the default). Therefore, the third option (official website statements with the deprecated rank) are excluded.

Does this make sense? Sorry for the verbosity :sweat\_smile:

gitlab2prov9fb82923-ff12-5ca6-aae9-a494c.gitlab2provissue_description: Sci-Hub has been added to the spam blacklist globally for all Wikimedia projects, including Wikidata. The reason is obvious (copyright violation), so de-blacklisting is unlikely. Unfortunately, it means that no one can add new URLs to the Sci-Hub Wikidata item (nor edit the ones that are already added). In particular, I failed to add the new URL [sci-hub.si](https://sci-hub.si) (also, there is [sci-hub.ltd](https://sci-hub.ltd), not sure if it's provided by Sci-Hub). In [the discussion of this issue](https://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Talk:Spam_blacklist/Archives/2020-01#d:Q21980377_(Sci-Hub)), the stewards didn't mind adding the URL but said "I don't think we can do anything really here" and "This likely needs a phab ticket to really get to a proper solution". Consequently, there should be a way to add new URLs other than adding them to Wikidata.

gitlab2prove19412b8-e9cd-5302-beec-bd307.gitlab2provissue_description:
Hello,

I'm developping a plugin for Chromium base and Firefox browsers and I'm using your work to redirect scientific articles to sci-hub (using the URL). Here's my plugin : https://github.com/RoiArthurB/Side-Auto_Sci-Hub

But recently, I had an issue with your redirect : It's interpreting GET parameters and drop them. So if I try to use your redirect for that link : 
> https://www.osapublishing.org/ol/abstract.cfm?uri=ol-37-3-353
I get that URL : 
> https://whereisscihub.now.sh/go/https://www.osapublishing.org/ol/abstract.cfm?uri=ol-37-3-353

And the result is something not working and which have drop GET parameters : 
> https://sci-hub.se/https%3A%2F%2Fwww.osapublishing.org%2Fol%2Fabstract.cfm

I tried directly the expected link ( https://sci-hub.se/https://www.osapublishing.org/ol/abstract.cfm?uri=ol-37-3-353 ) and it's working perfectly. So the problem is that your redirect drop GET parameters.

Do you have any clue on how to fix it? I planned to read your code to PR a fix, but if you have any informations to start on it it'll be helpful ! :smile: 

PS: Thanks for your work, it helped me a lot for my plugin ! Love u :heart:

gitlab2prov84739deb-d948-5f7c-a1e9-81b77.gitlab2provissue_description:
To fully benefit from the advantages of CI/CD, developers need to follow certain principles. Many of these principles have been introduced in the landmark book [Continuous Delivery: Reliable Software Releases through Build, Test, and Deployment Automation](https://www.oreilly.com/library/view/continuous-delivery-reliable/9780321670250/) and are nowadays widely accepted. One of these principles is:

> The build process has to be fully automated. 
Manual steps might introduce errors and delay the delivery of code changes to the clients.

**Problem**: We analyzed your project and found that the job `stop_review` in your [GitLab config](https://gitlab.com/Flockademic/whereisscihub/blob/master/.gitlab-ci.yml#L28) (line 28) violates this principle, because it is set to be executed manually.

```
stop_review:
    ...
    when:manual
    ...
```

**Suggested Fix:** Remove ```when:manual``` from the job definition to execute the job on every build.

**Disclaimer:**
This issue has been automatically reported by [CD-Linter](https://bitbucket.org/sealuzh/cd-linter/), a tool developed at the [University of Zurich](https://www.uzh.ch/) that detects CI/CD violations in the GitLab CI/CD pipeline configuration.
We are currently evaluating the effectiveness of our tool and we are monitoring this issue.

*Please up/downvote this issue to indicate whether you agree/disagree with the report.*
gitlab2prov84739deb-d948-5f7c-a1e9-81b77.gitlab2provissue_title: GitLab config: Job 'stop_review' is manually triggered

gitlab2provba2efd58-a922-5f47-9f29-107d4.gitlab2provissue_description:
I noticed that query strings after go/ seem not to work anymore.

Apparently the fault is with sci-hub since this:

    https://whereisscihub.now.sh/go/https%3A%2F%2Fjournals.aps.org%2Fprl%2Fpdf%2F10.1103%2FPhysRevLett.79.2213

redirects to this:

    http://80.82.77.83/https%3A%2F%2Fjournals.aps.org%2Fprl%2Fpdf%2F10.1103%2FPhysRevLett.79.2213

which then (redirects? loads?) this:

    https://sci-hub.se/

and not this (which would have caused the correct article to be downloaded):

    https://sci-hub.se/https%3A%2F%2Fjournals.aps.org%2Fprl%2Fpdf%2F10.1103%2FPhysRevLett.79.2213

I know this is not your bug, but I'm wondering if something can be done on either side to fix it. Thank you for your service, in any case.

gitlab2provfb5fd492-5c14-59d7-8d20-7b4e8.gitlab2provissue_description:
There are nice instructions in the README for running the project, but they're somewhat generic to similar node.js apps. (In fact, I'm not even sure I understand why it couldn't be a simple client-side webpage, but that's another issue.)

It would be great to have some brief overview of how the project actually works (i.e. "implementation notes"), for example listing which files are the main ones and what their content and purpose is.

The ideal, IMO, would be something similar to [this README](https://github.com/sidneycadot/oeis#oeis-tools), but any small steps in that direction would already be quite helpful to help others know where and how to contribute. I'd say the bare minimum should be a one-sentence description of what the project is/does, and a link to the live demo. Anything beyond that would be welcome additions, of course.
gitlab2provfb5fd492-5c14-59d7-8d20-7b4e8.gitlab2provissue_title: Add project documentation to the README
